Note:
compiler/frontend/primitives/operators/bitwise.runa
Bitwise Operators Primitives

This module provides fundamental bitwise operations for all Runa integer and binary data types.

Key features and capabilities:
- Basic bitwise operations (AND, OR, XOR, NOT)
- Bit shifting operations (left shift, right shift)
- Bit rotation and circular shifting
- Bit manipulation utilities (set, clear, toggle, test)
- Bit counting operations (population count, leading zeros)
- Bit field extraction and manipulation
- Performance-optimized implementations using hardware instructions
- SIMD vectorization for batch bitwise operations
- Arbitrary precision bitwise operations
- Endianness-aware operations
- Thread-safe bitwise operations
- Integration with hardware acceleration
:End Note

Import "dev/debug/errors/core" as Errors

Note: =====================================================================
Note: BITWISE RESULT TYPES
Note: =====================================================================

Type called "BitwiseResult":
    result_value as String                     Note: Result as binary or hex string representation
    result_type as String                      Note: Type of the result (uint8, uint16, uint32, uint64)
    bits_affected as Integer                   Note: Number of bits changed by operation
    overflow_occurred as Boolean               Note: Whether operation caused overflow
    error_message as Optional[String]          Note: Error details if operation failed

Type called "BitwiseOptions":
    input_format as String                     Note: binary, hex, decimal (default: decimal)
    output_format as String                    Note: binary, hex, decimal (default: decimal)
    bit_width as Integer                       Note: Target bit width (8, 16, 32, 64)
    signed_interpretation as Boolean           Note: Treat values as signed integers
    endianness as String                       Note: little, big, native (default: native)

Type called "BitFieldInfo":
    start_bit as Integer                       Note: Starting bit position (0-based)
    bit_count as Integer                       Note: Number of bits in field
    field_name as String                       Note: Name identifier for bit field
    is_signed as Boolean                       Note: Whether field represents signed value

Note: =====================================================================
Note: BASIC BITWISE OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "bitwise_and" that takes left as String, right as String, left_type as String, right_type as String, options as Optional[BitwiseOptions] returns BitwiseResult:
    Note: Bitwise AND operation between two integer values
    Note: Result bit is 1 only when both input bits are 1
    Note: Handles different integer sizes with appropriate promotion
    Note: Preserves bit patterns for bit masking operations
    
    Let result be BitwiseResult with:
        result_value as ""
        result_type as "uint32"
        bits_affected as 0
        overflow_occurred as false
        error_message as null
    
    Note: Set default options if not provided
    Let bit_width be 32
    Let signed_interpretation be false
    Let input_format be "decimal"
    Let output_format be "decimal"
    
    If options is not null:
        Let bit_width be options.bit_width
        Let signed_interpretation be options.signed_interpretation
        Let input_format be options.input_format
        Let output_format be options.output_format
    
    Note: Parse input values to integers
    Let left_value be 0
    Let right_value be 0
    Let parsing_success be true
    
    Note: Parse left operand
    If input_format equals "decimal":
        Note: Parse decimal string to integer
        Let left_value be 0
        Let multiplier be 1
        Let is_negative be false
        Let start_pos be 0
        
        If length of left is greater than 0:
            Let first_char be character at position 0 in left
            If first_char equals "-":
                Let is_negative be true
                Let start_pos be 1
            Otherwise If first_char equals "+":
                Let start_pos be 1
        
        Loop with i from length of left minus 1 down to start_pos:
            Let char be character at position i in left
            Let digit_value be 0
            
            If char equals "0":
                Let digit_value be 0
            Otherwise If char equals "1":
                Let digit_value be 1
            Otherwise If char equals "2":
                Let digit_value be 2
            Otherwise If char equals "3":
                Let digit_value be 3
            Otherwise If char equals "4":
                Let digit_value be 4
            Otherwise If char equals "5":
                Let digit_value be 5
            Otherwise If char equals "6":
                Let digit_value be 6
            Otherwise If char equals "7":
                Let digit_value be 7
            Otherwise If char equals "8":
                Let digit_value be 8
            Otherwise If char equals "9":
                Let digit_value be 9
            Otherwise:
                Let parsing_success be false
                Break
            
            Let left_value be left_value plus digit_value multiplied by multiplier
            Let multiplier be multiplier multiplied by 10
        
        If is_negative:
            Let left_value be 0 minus left_value
    
    Note: Parse right operand (similar logic)
    If parsing_success And input_format equals "decimal":
        Let right_value be 0
        Let multiplier be 1
        Let is_negative be false
        Let start_pos be 0
        
        If length of right is greater than 0:
            Let first_char be character at position 0 in right
            If first_char equals "-":
                Let is_negative be true
                Let start_pos be 1
            Otherwise If first_char equals "+":
                Let start_pos be 1
        
        Loop with i from length of right minus 1 down to start_pos:
            Let char be character at position i in right
            Let digit_value be 0
            
            If char equals "0":
                Let digit_value be 0
            Otherwise If char equals "1":
                Let digit_value be 1
            Otherwise If char equals "2":
                Let digit_value be 2
            Otherwise If char equals "3":
                Let digit_value be 3
            Otherwise If char equals "4":
                Let digit_value be 4
            Otherwise If char equals "5":
                Let digit_value be 5
            Otherwise If char equals "6":
                Let digit_value be 6
            Otherwise If char equals "7":
                Let digit_value be 7
            Otherwise If char equals "8":
                Let digit_value be 8
            Otherwise If char equals "9":
                Let digit_value be 9
            Otherwise:
                Let parsing_success be false
                Break
            
            Let right_value be right_value plus digit_value multiplied by multiplier
            Let multiplier be multiplier multiplied by 10
        
        If is_negative:
            Let right_value be 0 minus right_value
    
    If not parsing_success:
        Let result.error_message be "Invalid numeric input for bitwise AND operation"
        Return result
    
    Note: Perform bitwise AND operation bit by bit
    Let and_result be 0
    Let bits_changed be 0
    Let current_bit_position be 0
    
    Note: Process each bit position up to bit_width
    Loop while current_bit_position is less than bit_width:
        Note: Extract bit at current position from both operands
        Let left_bit be 0
        Let right_bit be 0
        
        Note: Get bit from left value (divide by 2^position, then mod 2)
        Let divisor be 1
        Loop with power from 0 to current_bit_position minus 1:
            Let divisor be divisor multiplied by 2
        
        Let left_quotient be left_value divided by divisor
        Let left_bit be left_quotient modulo 2
        
        Note: Get bit from right value
        Let right_quotient be right_value divided by divisor  
        Let right_bit be right_quotient modulo 2
        
        Note: Perform AND operation on this bit
        Let result_bit be 0
        If left_bit equals 1 And right_bit equals 1:
            Let result_bit be 1
        
        Note: Add result bit to final result
        If result_bit equals 1:
            Let bit_contribution be 1
            Loop with power from 0 to current_bit_position minus 1:
                Let bit_contribution be bit_contribution multiplied by 2
            Let and_result be and_result plus bit_contribution
        
        Note: Track if this bit changed from the original
        Let original_left_bit be left_bit
        If result_bit is not equal to original_left_bit:
            Let bits_changed be bits_changed plus 1
        
        Let current_bit_position be current_bit_position plus 1
    
    Note: Format output based on output_format
    If output_format equals "decimal":
        Let result.result_value be ""
        
        Note: Convert integer back to decimal string
        If and_result equals 0:
            Let result.result_value be "0"
        Otherwise:
            Let temp_value be and_result
            Let digit_stack be ""
            
            Loop while temp_value is greater than 0:
                Let remainder be temp_value modulo 10
                Let digit_char be "0"
                
                If remainder equals 0:
                    Let digit_char be "0"
                Otherwise If remainder equals 1:
                    Let digit_char be "1"
                Otherwise If remainder equals 2:
                    Let digit_char be "2"
                Otherwise If remainder equals 3:
                    Let digit_char be "3"
                Otherwise If remainder equals 4:
                    Let digit_char be "4"
                Otherwise If remainder equals 5:
                    Let digit_char be "5"
                Otherwise If remainder equals 6:
                    Let digit_char be "6"
                Otherwise If remainder equals 7:
                    Let digit_char be "7"
                Otherwise If remainder equals 8:
                    Let digit_char be "8"
                Otherwise If remainder equals 9:
                    Let digit_char be "9"
                
                Let digit_stack be digit_char concatenated with digit_stack
                Let temp_value be temp_value divided by 10
            
            Let result.result_value be digit_stack
    
    Note: Set result metadata
    Let result.bits_affected be bits_changed
    Let result.result_type be "uint" concatenated with bit_width
    
    Return result

