            Otherwise If remainder equals 3:
                Let digit_char be "3"
            Otherwise If remainder equals 4:
                Let digit_char be "4"
            Otherwise If remainder equals 5:
                Let digit_char be "5"
            Otherwise If remainder equals 6:
                Let digit_char be "6"
            Otherwise If remainder equals 7:
                Let digit_char be "7"
            Otherwise If remainder equals 8:
                Let digit_char be "8"
            Otherwise If remainder equals 9:
                Let digit_char be "9"
            
            Let digit_stack be digit_char concatenated with digit_stack
            Let temp_value be temp_value divided by 10
        
        Let result.result_value be digit_stack
    
    Note: Set result metadata
    Let result.result_type be value_type
    Let result.bit_width be bit_width
    Let result.is_valid be true
    Let result.operations_performed be 1
    Return result

Note: =====================================================================
Note: VECTORIZED BITWISE OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "vector_bitwise_and" that takes left_values as List[String], right_values as List[String], element_type as String returns List[BitwiseResult]:
    Note: Element-wise bitwise AND of two integer vectors
    Note: SIMD optimization for compatible types and platforms
    Note: Handles vector length validation and alignment
    
    Note: Create result list to store individual operations
    Let results be List[BitwiseResult] with:
        capacity as length of left_values
        elements as empty
    
    Note: Validate vector lengths match
    If length of left_values is not equal to length of right_values:
        Note: Create error result for mismatched vector lengths
        Let error_result be BitwiseResult with:
            is_valid as false
            error_code as "vector_length_mismatch"
            error_message as "Left and right vectors must have the same length"
            result_value as ""
            result_type as element_type
            operation as "vector_bitwise_and"
            operands as ""
            bit_width as null
            signed_result as null
            overflow_occurred as false
            underflow_occurred as false
            precision_lost as false
            operations_performed as 0
            execution_time_ms as null
        
        Add error_result to results
        Return results
    
    Note: Validate vectors are not empty
    If length of left_values equals 0:
        Note: Return empty results for empty input
        Return results
    
    Note: Process each element pair
    Loop with i from 0 to length of left_values minus 1:
        Let left_element be element at position i in left_values
        Let right_element be element at position i in right_values
        
        Note: Perform bitwise AND on this element pair
        Let element_result be bitwise_and with left_element, right_element, element_type, element_type, null
        
        Note: Update operation name to indicate vector operation
        Let element_result.operation be "vector_bitwise_and[" concatenated with i concatenated with "]"
        
        Add element_result to results
    
    Return results

Process called "vector_bitwise_or" that takes left_values as List[String], right_values as List[String], element_type as String returns List[BitwiseResult]:
    Note: Element-wise bitwise OR of two integer vectors
    Note: Supports broadcasting for scalar-vector operations
    Note: Efficient batch processing for large datasets
    
    Note: Create result list to store individual operations
    Let results be List[BitwiseResult] with:
        capacity as length of left_values
        elements as empty
    
    Note: Handle broadcasting - if one vector has length 1, broadcast it
    Let left_is_scalar be false
    Let right_is_scalar be false
    
    If length of left_values equals 1 And length of right_values is greater than 1:
        Let left_is_scalar be true
    
    If length of right_values equals 1 And length of left_values is greater than 1:
        Let right_is_scalar be true
    
    Note: Validate vector length compatibility
    Let target_length be 0
    If left_is_scalar:
        Let target_length be length of right_values
    Otherwise If right_is_scalar:
        Let target_length be length of left_values
    Otherwise If length of left_values equals length of right_values:
        Let target_length be length of left_values
    Otherwise:
        Note: Create error result for incompatible vector lengths
        Let error_result be BitwiseResult with:
            is_valid as false
            error_code as "vector_length_incompatible"
            error_message as "Vector lengths are incompatible for broadcasting"
            result_value as ""
            result_type as element_type
            operation as "vector_bitwise_or"
            operands as ""
            bit_width as null
            signed_result as null
            overflow_occurred as false
            underflow_occurred as false
            precision_lost as false
            operations_performed as 0
            execution_time_ms as null
        
        Add error_result to results
        Return results
    
    Note: Validate vectors are not empty
    If target_length equals 0:
        Note: Return empty results for empty input
        Return results
    
    Note: Process each element pair with broadcasting
    Loop with i from 0 to target_length minus 1:
        Let left_element be ""
        Let right_element be ""
        
        Note: Get left element (broadcast if scalar)
        If left_is_scalar:
            Let left_element be element at position 0 in left_values
        Otherwise:
            Let left_element be element at position i in left_values
        
        Note: Get right element (broadcast if scalar)
        If right_is_scalar:
            Let right_element be element at position 0 in right_values
        Otherwise:
            Let right_element be element at position i in right_values
        
        Note: Perform bitwise OR on this element pair
        Let element_result be bitwise_or with left_element, right_element, element_type, element_type, null
        
        Note: Update operation name to indicate vector operation
        Let element_result.operation be "vector_bitwise_or[" concatenated with i concatenated with "]"
        
        Add element_result to results
    
    Return results

Note: =====================================================================
Note: BITWISE UTILITY OPERATIONS
Note: =====================================================================

Process called "format_as_binary" that takes value as String, value_type as String, options as Optional[BitwiseOptions] returns String:
    Note: Format integer value as binary string
    Note: Includes leading zeros to show full bit width
    Note: Optional grouping (nibbles, bytes) for readability
    
    Note: Parse and validate input
    Let input_value be 0
    Let is_negative be false
    
    Note: Check for negative number
    If value starts with "-":
        Let is_negative be true
        Let value be value from index 1 to end
    
    Note: Convert string to integer
    Loop with i from 0 to length of value minus 1:
        Let char be character at index i in value
        Let digit_value be 0
        
        If char equals "0":
            Let digit_value be 0
        Otherwise If char equals "1":
            Let digit_value be 1
        Otherwise If char equals "2":
            Let digit_value be 2
        Otherwise If char equals "3":
            Let digit_value be 3
        Otherwise If char equals "4":
            Let digit_value be 4
        Otherwise If char equals "5":
            Let digit_value be 5
        Otherwise If char equals "6":
            Let digit_value be 6
        Otherwise If char equals "7":
            Let digit_value be 7
        Otherwise If char equals "8":
            Let digit_value be 8
        Otherwise If char equals "9":
            Let digit_value be 9
        Otherwise:
            Return "ERROR: Invalid numeric character"
        
        Let input_value be input_value multiplied by 10 plus digit_value
    
    Note: Apply negative sign
    If is_negative:
        Let input_value be 0 minus input_value
    
    Note: Get bit width from value type
    Let bit_width be 32
    If value_type contains "8":
        Let bit_width be 8
    Otherwise If value_type contains "16":
        Let bit_width be 16  
    Otherwise If value_type contains "32":
        Let bit_width be 32
    Otherwise If value_type contains "64":
        Let bit_width be 64
    
    Note: Handle negative values by converting to unsigned representation
    If input_value is less than 0:
        Let max_value be 1
        Loop with i from 0 to bit_width minus 1:
            Let max_value be max_value multiplied by 2
        Let input_value be input_value plus max_value
    
    Note: Extract bits and build binary string
    Let binary_string be ""
    
    Loop with bit_pos from bit_width minus 1 down to 0:
        Note: Calculate divisor for this bit position (2^bit_pos)
        Let divisor be 1
        Loop with j from 0 to bit_pos minus 1:
            Let divisor be divisor multiplied by 2
        
        Note: Extract the bit
        Let quotient be input_value divided by divisor
        Let bit_value be quotient modulo 2
        
        Note: Add bit to binary string
        If bit_value equals 1:
            Let binary_string be binary_string concatenated with "1"
        Otherwise:
            Let binary_string be binary_string concatenated with "0"
    
    Note: Apply grouping if specified in options
    Let group_size be 0
    Let add_prefix be false
    
    If options is not null:
        If options.output_format equals "nibbles":
            Let group_size be 4
        Otherwise If options.output_format equals "bytes":
            Let group_size be 8
        
        If options.input_format equals "prefixed":
            Let add_prefix be true
    
    Note: Apply grouping with spaces
    If group_size is greater than 0:
        Let grouped_string be ""
        Let char_count be 0
        
        Loop with i from 0 to length of binary_string minus 1:
            Let char be character at index i in binary_string
            Let grouped_string be grouped_string concatenated with char
            Let char_count be char_count plus 1
            
            Note: Add space after each group (except at the end)
            If char_count modulo group_size equals 0 And i is less than length of binary_string minus 1:
                Let grouped_string be grouped_string concatenated with " "
        
        Let binary_string be grouped_string
    
    Note: Add prefix if requested
    If add_prefix:
        Let binary_string be "0b" concatenated with binary_string
    
    Return binary_string

Process called "parse_binary_string" that takes binary_str as String, target_type as String returns BitwiseResult:
    Note: Parse binary string representation to integer value
    Note: Handles optional prefixes (0b, 0B) and separators
    Note: Validates binary string format and range
    
    Let result be BitwiseResult with:
        is_valid as false
        error_code as null
        error_message as null
        result_value as ""
        result_type as ""
        operation as "parse_binary_string"
        operands as binary_str
        bit_width as null
        signed_result as null
        overflow_occurred as false
        underflow_occurred as false
        precision_lost as false
        operations_performed as 0
        execution_time_ms as null
    
    Note: Clean the binary string (remove prefix and separators)
    Let cleaned_binary be binary_str
    
    Note: Remove common prefixes
    If cleaned_binary starts with "0b" Or cleaned_binary starts with "0B":
        Let cleaned_binary be cleaned_binary from index 2 to end
    
    Note: Remove spaces and underscores (common separators)
    Let final_binary be ""
    Loop with i from 0 to length of cleaned_binary minus 1:
        Let char be character at index i in cleaned_binary
        If char is not equal to " " And char is not equal to "_":
            Let final_binary be final_binary concatenated with char
    
    Note: Validate binary string contains only 0s and 1s
    Loop with i from 0 to length of final_binary minus 1:
        Let char be character at index i in final_binary
        If char is not equal to "0" And char is not equal to "1":
            Let result.error_code be "invalid_binary_character"
            Let result.error_message be "Binary string contains invalid character: " concatenated with char
            Return result
    
    Note: Validate binary string is not empty
    If length of final_binary equals 0:
        Let result.error_code be "empty_binary_string"
        Let result.error_message be "Binary string is empty after cleaning"
        Return result
    
    Note: Get bit width from target type
    Let bit_width be 32
    If target_type contains "8":
        Let bit_width be 8
    Otherwise If target_type contains "16":
        Let bit_width be 16  
    Otherwise If target_type contains "32":
        Let bit_width be 32
    Otherwise If target_type contains "64":
        Let bit_width be 64
    
    Note: Validate binary string length doesn't exceed bit width
    If length of final_binary is greater than bit_width:
        Let result.error_code be "binary_string_too_long"
        Let result.error_message be "Binary string exceeds target type bit width"
        Return result
    
    Note: Convert binary string to decimal value
    Let decimal_value be 0
    Let bit_position be 0
    
    Note: Process bits from right to left (LSB to MSB)
    Loop with i from length of final_binary minus 1 down to 0:
        Let bit_char be character at index i in final_binary
        
        If bit_char equals "1":
            Note: Add 2^bit_position to result
            Let bit_contribution be 1
            Loop with j from 0 to bit_position minus 1:
                Let bit_contribution be bit_contribution multiplied by 2
            Let decimal_value be decimal_value plus bit_contribution
        
        Let bit_position be bit_position plus 1
    
    Note: Validate result fits in target type range
    Let max_value be 1
    Loop with i from 0 to bit_width minus 1:
        Let max_value be max_value multiplied by 2
    Let max_value be max_value minus 1
    
    If decimal_value is greater than max_value:
        Let result.overflow_occurred be true
        Let decimal_value be max_value
    
    Note: Convert result back to decimal string
    If decimal_value equals 0:
        Let result.result_value be "0"
    Otherwise:
        Let temp_value be decimal_value
        Let digit_stack be ""
        
        Loop while temp_value is greater than 0:
            Let remainder be temp_value modulo 10
            Let digit_char be "0"
            
            If remainder equals 0:
                Let digit_char be "0"
            Otherwise If remainder equals 1:
                Let digit_char be "1"
            Otherwise If remainder equals 2:
                Let digit_char be "2"
            Otherwise If remainder equals 3:
                Let digit_char be "3"
            Otherwise If remainder equals 4:
                Let digit_char be "4"
            Otherwise If remainder equals 5:
                Let digit_char be "5"
            Otherwise If remainder equals 6:
                Let digit_char be "6"
            Otherwise If remainder equals 7:
                Let digit_char be "7"
            Otherwise If remainder equals 8:
                Let digit_char be "8"
            Otherwise If remainder equals 9:
                Let digit_char be "9"
            
            Let digit_stack be digit_char concatenated with digit_stack
            Let temp_value be temp_value divided by 10
        
        Let result.result_value be digit_stack
    
    Note: Set result metadata
    Let result.result_type be target_type
    Let result.bit_width be bit_width
    Let result.is_valid be true
    Let result.operations_performed be 1
    Return result

Process called "calculate_bitwise_complexity" that takes operation as String, operand_types as List[String] returns Integer:
    Note: Estimate computational complexity of bitwise operation
    Note: Used for optimization and algorithm selection
    Note: Considers hardware acceleration availability
    
    Note: Base complexity score (lower is better)
    Let base_complexity be 0
    
    Note: Calculate bit width for complexity estimation
    Let max_bit_width be 32
    Loop with i from 0 to length of operand_types minus 1:
        Let operand_type be element at position i in operand_types
        Let current_bit_width be 32
        
        If operand_type contains "8":
            Let current_bit_width be 8
        Otherwise If operand_type contains "16":
            Let current_bit_width be 16
        Otherwise If operand_type contains "32":
            Let current_bit_width be 32
        Otherwise If operand_type contains "64":
            Let current_bit_width be 64
        
        If current_bit_width is greater than max_bit_width:
            Let max_bit_width be current_bit_width
    
    Note: Basic bitwise operations - O(bit_width) complexity
    If operation equals "bitwise_and":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 2
    Otherwise If operation equals "bitwise_or":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 2
    Otherwise If operation equals "bitwise_xor":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 2
    Otherwise If operation equals "bitwise_not":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width
    
    Note: Shift operations - O(bit_width) complexity
    Otherwise If operation equals "shift_left":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 3
    Otherwise If operation equals "shift_right":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 3
    
    Note: Rotation operations - O(bit_width) with additional OR overhead
    Otherwise If operation equals "rotate_left":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 5
    Otherwise If operation equals "rotate_right":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 4
    
    Note: Individual bit manipulation - O(bit_width) complexity
    Otherwise If operation equals "set_bit":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 3
    Otherwise If operation equals "clear_bit":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 4
    Otherwise If operation equals "toggle_bit":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 2
    Otherwise If operation equals "test_bit":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width
    
    Note: Bit counting operations - O(bit_width) complexity
    Otherwise If operation equals "count_set_bits":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 2
    Otherwise If operation equals "count_leading_zeros":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 2
    Otherwise If operation equals "count_trailing_zeros":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 2
    Otherwise If operation equals "find_first_set":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 2
    
    Note: Bit field operations - O(bit_width * field_size) complexity
    Otherwise If operation equals "extract_bit_field":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 4
    Otherwise If operation equals "insert_bit_field":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 6
    Otherwise If operation equals "create_bit_mask":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 2
    
    Note: Advanced operations - higher complexity
    Otherwise If operation equals "reverse_bits":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 3
    Otherwise If operation equals "gray_code_encode":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 4
    Otherwise If operation equals "gray_code_decode":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 4
    
    Note: Vectorized operations - multiply by vector length estimation
    Otherwise If operation equals "vector_bitwise_and":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 2 multiplied by 10
    Otherwise If operation equals "vector_bitwise_or":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 2 multiplied by 10
    
    Note: Utility operations - varies by operation
    Otherwise If operation equals "format_as_binary":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 3
    Otherwise If operation equals "parse_binary_string":
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 2
    
    Note: Unknown operation - high penalty
    Otherwise:
        Let base_complexity be max_bit_width multiplied by 10
    
    Note: Apply hardware acceleration multipliers (lower multiplier = better)
    Let hardware_multiplier be 1.0
    
    Note: Basic operations often have hardware support
    If operation equals "bitwise_and" Or operation equals "bitwise_or" Or operation equals "bitwise_xor" Or operation equals "bitwise_not":
        Let hardware_multiplier be 0.5
    
    Note: Shift operations typically have hardware support
    Otherwise If operation equals "shift_left" Or operation equals "shift_right":
        Let hardware_multiplier be 0.6
    
    Note: Population count may have hardware support (POPCNT instruction)
    Otherwise If operation equals "count_set_bits":
        Let hardware_multiplier be 0.7
    
    Note: Leading/trailing zero count may have hardware support (LZCNT/TZCNT)
    Otherwise If operation equals "count_leading_zeros" Or operation equals "count_trailing_zeros":
        Let hardware_multiplier be 0.8
    
    Note: Vector operations benefit from SIMD
    Otherwise If operation contains "vector_":
        Let hardware_multiplier be 0.3
    
    Note: Apply type-specific penalties
    Let type_penalty be 0
    
    Note: 64-bit operations may be slower on 32-bit systems
    If max_bit_width equals 64:
        Let type_penalty be 20
    
    Note: Mixed types require additional conversion overhead
    If length of operand_types is greater than 1:
        Let first_type be element at position 0 in operand_types
        Loop with i from 1 to length of operand_types minus 1:
            Let current_type be element at position i in operand_types
            If current_type is not equal to first_type:
                Let type_penalty be type_penalty plus 10
                Break
    
    Note: Calculate final complexity score
    Let final_complexity be base_complexity
    Let adjusted_complexity be final_complexity multiplied by hardware_multiplier
    Let final_complexity be adjusted_complexity plus type_penalty
    
    Note: Ensure minimum complexity of 1
    If final_complexity is less than 1:
        Let final_complexity be 1
    
    Note: Convert to integer (truncate decimal part)
    Let integer_complexity be final_complexity divided by 1
    
    Return integer_complexity